br>
<br>
<br>
These are some significant reasons to become vegetarian. If you care virtually nothing for animals, that's fine. Vegetarianism does not always have to be about animal rights and love of animals as it is often seen exclusively to be; this kind of research shows that vegetarianism can be about love for humanity as well. So vegetarianism can also be for the many who believe human welfare is more important than animal welfare... Because not only is it a healthier diet for most people (if you eat correctly and balance), if it becomes widespread enough it could help ensure that our resources don't dwindle as quickly, and that humankind could potentially survive for longer sustained by this planet. Idealism? Probably. But the more people that decide to have a vegetarian lifestyle, the better it can be for so many aspects of life.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I am not talking vegetarianism here- I am talking veganism. Do you really want me to tell you the health reasons for changing your diet?? (like how much of cows milk is made up of pus).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Oh dear, didn't know that. *puke*. Ahem. Anyway... Veganism can be a good concept, however it tends to be much less realistic than vegetarianism and here's why... For one, human development relies heavily on calcium from milk and protein from eggs, etc. Many people would not be willing to give up their precious fatty foods even when confronted with such compelling evidence such as possible heart disease and cancer. Also, veganism requires much more work to maintain diet and nutrition. There are supplements and such out there, but let's face it, people are lazy in general. I can't even remember to take a daily vitamin, let alone figure out the supplements for all that I need in my diet which I would not be getting from milk and egg products. People would have to be pretty informed and educated on the subject of nutrition in order to eat healthily on that sort of diet, or else some might end up in a worse situation than if they had been eating tons of milk and cheese et cetera all their lives. Malnutrition is always a significant concern, and it tends to be pretty common in vegans and often even vegetarians. It's a heavy personal decision that has to be carefully considered... And most of the world does not seem ready for veganism. <p></p><span class=m><i></i></span><hr size=1>   &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fbbardenfrm57.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=38.topic&index=4><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/reply.gif border=0 width=20 height=20 alt="reply to this message" align=absmiddle></a>   <br><br></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 bgcolor=#FFFFFF><table cellpadding=5 cellspacing=0 width=100%><tr><td align=right class=headings> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fbbardenfrm57.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=38.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"></a>  <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fbba